I"e<p>In our household, we have a few ground rules about how we communicate with other humans. We don’t pretend butter is gross, we <a class="internal-link" href="/stop-saying-race">don’t say “race”</a>, and we don’t think books are, by default, better than their film adaptations.</p>

<p>From Wikipedia:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>Visual literacy is the ability to <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpreting" title="Interpreting">interpret</a>, negotiate, and make meaning from information presented in the form of an <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image" title="Image">image</a>, extending the meaning of <a href="https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Literacy" title="Literacy">literacy</a>, which commonly signifies interpretation of a written or printed text.
— <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visual_literacy">Wikipedia</a></p>
</blockquote>

